00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:24.310
 So today we have three topics we're going to discuss in this chapter "Cultivating Bodhichitta", and

00:02:24.310 --> 00:02:31.850
 then the first here, basically I'll just summarize the first section of this chapter really quickly

00:02:31.850 --> 00:02:32.000
.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:39.170
 The Veneroble Khenpo Rinpoches first say that achieving enlightenment totally depends on one's own

00:02:39.170 --> 00:02:43.000
 effort, and that the best way to become enlightened is with bodhichitta.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:48.310
 And this bodhichitta has two aspects, this relative aspect of feeling and expressing love and

00:02:48.310 --> 00:02:54.900
 compassion for all beings, and then the absolute aspect of realizing the empty nature of all

00:02:54.900 --> 00:02:58.000
 phenomena, oneself and all others.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:07.000
 So the first point summarized in a paragraph on page 33, which is the second paragraph.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:13.690
 The root of bodhichitta is compassion. Compassion is feeling deep in your heart the suffering of

00:03:13.690 --> 00:03:17.000
 others, and wishing for them to be free from all pain.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:22.360
 The root of compassion is loving kindness, which is the feeling of wanting to replace suffering

00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:24.000
 with happiness and peace.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:29.000
 Having true love and compassion for everyone is the most precious practice of the Dharma.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:37.000
 Without this, your practice will remain superficial and never be deeply rooted in the true Dharma.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:49.840
 I have a question. So here they say having true love and compassion for everyone is the most

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:56.000
 precious practice, and without this, your practice will never be rooted in the true Dharma.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:02.050
 So that's a tall order, right from the beginning, because you have to have love and compassion for

00:04:02.050 --> 00:04:03.000
 everyone.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.210
 And if we're sentient beings, the definition of sentient beings is they don't have love and

00:04:08.210 --> 00:04:10.000
 compassion for everyone.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.500
 You know, I mean, they're self-centered. You know, we have the five poisons, if you're an ordinary

00:04:14.500 --> 00:04:15.000
 being.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:24.000
 So how do we even start to begin to cultivate loving kindness and compassion for everyone?

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:34.000
 That's not where many of us, such as myself, don't naturally just start out there. Any thoughts?

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:41.960
 It seems the first thing is that that's kind of like the view to start with at least. And why is

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:49.090
 that? Because, I mean, that's how the natural state is, or how the enlightened mind is in that way,

00:04:49.090 --> 00:04:50.000
 it seems.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:57.020
 And just kind of an underlying thing. You can have this aspiration, but it's kind of a view that's

00:04:57.020 --> 00:05:05.000
 showing to start out from, like, what is the source and the goal and all of that with the practice.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:10.780
 And there's more to be said, but it just seems like that's a general frame. I mean, that comes to

00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:15.000
 mind first. I'm sure other people have what it comes to.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:30.000
 And of course, there's people we can relate to who we do love and who we do see suffer.

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:38.040
 And it seems like that can be, I don't know, it's like a doorway to all beings. We can think of one

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:45.000
 being who we love and don't want to suffer and want to be free of suffering.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:52.380
 And can, like, kind of have that be like a gateway to engaging with our authentic feeling and

00:05:52.380 --> 00:05:57.000
 thinking about how we wish that for everyone.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:02.780
 And think about how who knows all the ways in which we're related to that one person and how,

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:12.550
 really, according to the Buddhist teachings, everyone we've had close relationships with in the

00:06:12.550 --> 00:06:13.000
 past.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:20.670
 But just in that way, beginning to think about real beings who are in our life and in our world who

00:06:20.670 --> 00:06:28.600
 we can relate to and just remembering there's more, you know, and keeping our aspiration open and

00:06:28.600 --> 00:06:32.000
 engaging with that to the best of our abilities.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:39.070
 I think another way, too, is really contemplating the, kind of, just the enlightened qualities of

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:45.000
 the Buddhists and, like, seeing, like, thinking about that they can do this.

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:52.100
 And, you know, like our teachers tell us in this chapter about how, you know, our bodhicitta at

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:59.230
 this time may be small, but it is within our potential to develop this total vast limitless bodhic

00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:03.000
itta, boundless bodhicitta, that it is possible.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:09.070
 And we trust that, we trust what our teachers say, we contemplate what these enlightened beings, we

00:07:09.070 --> 00:07:15.740
 read about their lives and that they've done this and inspire us and, kind of, sort of, that trust

00:07:15.740 --> 00:07:17.000
 that we can do it.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.750
 And then, like you were saying, like, developing that aspiration and wish that we're really strong,

00:07:22.750 --> 00:07:29.000
 getting stronger, and it seems maybe at that point, maybe they'll lead into this next discussion

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:31.000
 about the absolute bodhicitta where we

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:38.940
 start understanding that, oh, maybe it's not so limited, you know, there is more space available,

00:07:38.940 --> 00:07:43.000
 there is more, more possible than I currently think.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:50.000
 And that, kind of, can be our bridge to bringing relative and absolute bodhicitta, too, together.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.010
 I think, going off of what you're saying, too, I remember one of the first books I read in Buddhism

00:07:55.010 --> 00:08:00.580
 was one of the Dalai Lama's books. I think it was called "How to Expand Bodhicitta," but a lot of

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:05.000
 the way he wrote the book was tinkering with your view.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:06.930
 He'd give these, kind of, hypotheticals or meditation on, think of someone who you're close to and

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:16.470
 then think about, essentially exactly what Lai was saying, thinking about all those shared

00:08:16.470 --> 00:08:20.000
 qualities, and now expand that out to someone who you feel more neutral towards.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:27.110
 Okay, now that you've practiced that, expand that out to someone who it's not very easy for you to

00:08:27.110 --> 00:08:34.180
 feel loving towards. You know, you're expanding, expanding, and particularly the way that he goes

00:08:34.180 --> 00:08:35.000
 about it.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.300
 And I think the same, I see a lot of the same thing with all of the great teachers is you start

00:08:40.300 --> 00:08:46.440
 tinkering with the view, which goes a lot into what I think Amanda also said, you know, you tinker

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:49.000
 with the view, and when you're tinkering with the view,

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:55.690
 you start to realize that the narrow view that you were holding isn't some absolute thing, it isn't

00:08:55.690 --> 00:09:04.000
 some permanent thing. It gives that little bit of a gap. That gap is where so much potential is.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:11.900
 I think, although this only applies to people who have met a great teacher, I find that just

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:20.330
 thinking of how you feel around the teacher, what the teacher gives all, it's like, okay, that must

00:09:20.330 --> 00:09:21.000
 be it.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.340
 So it's kind of like right there for you, it's kind of like thinking of a parent being that's

00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:35.000
 saying, well, I think it's great, but it's hard if you don't have a teacher.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.530
 I don't think even before what I was saying, think about those people who are compassionate in your

00:09:39.530 --> 00:09:40.000
 life.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:45.490
 You know, even, I mean, of course, you know, someone who's just nice to you on the street maybe won

00:09:45.490 --> 00:09:53.000
't give you the same burst of compassion that, you know, going and seeing Kenpo, but it's a start.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:58.060
 And I think, too, the real basis of the question is so we're all, I mean, sentient beings

00:09:58.060 --> 00:10:05.000
 experiencing kind of the own difficulties that are kind of always kind of coming back at us.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:09.710
 And I think that really is the springboard, like in that chapter on taking refuge that we went over

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:14.130
, I mean, Amanda said, part of it is we have to recognize these enlightened qualities of the great

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:16.000
 masters that are really out of samsara.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:22.000
 They're no longer producing the negative emotions and the grasping that causes all these troubles.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:27.150
 And at the same time, the other side of that is to see, well, what is the cause of these troubles

00:10:27.150 --> 00:10:28.000
 of samsara?

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:33.420
 And it is our own grasping mind and own kind of negative emotions and more limited, narrow ways of

00:10:33.420 --> 00:10:37.000
 functioning our minds, tightening our heart, closing.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
 And then we see that in our own experience.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
 And we see that, okay, I do, there is some difficulty here.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:44.000
 How do I get out?

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
 So that's the first two noble truths.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:49.000
 And like, so we have compassion for ourselves.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:50.000
 There is a problem here.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.000
 And it's a genuine problem when we really start to see, this isn't permanent.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:55.000
 I keep doing these things.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
 They keep causing me trouble.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:01.000
 I don't want to do them as much, but I keep doing them.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:02.000
 And then we need to have compassion.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:05.000
 Okay, is there a way out?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:11.060
 So then there's a little more air in the room, a little more searching for what might help me come

00:11:11.060 --> 00:11:12.000
 out of this.

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.000
 And then at the same time, we can identify other people.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
 Oh, that person is hurting too.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
 Oh, that person is going through this other thing I went through already.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:23.000
 And then we kind of enlarging this fear like Lodra is saying.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:29.000
 And then keeping in mind this greater view of these great beings that have freely, fully activated

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:34.000
 and even in some cases completely realized the beautiful nature of their mind and their heart.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:39.000
 And then we see living examples of these great masters and can directly experience that.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
 And it uplifts us.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:49.000
 It shows us a way of how compassion is so strong and so capable and so flexible and so grounded

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:54.000
 and so functional and so just really so desirable.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:00.000
 It's the most desirable thing in samsara in our desire realm of constantly clean

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.000
 to try to move towards this love and compassion for ourselves and for others.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:11.690
 But I think the basis is seeing how we don't have that at the same time staying with that larger

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:12.000
 view.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:18.000
 But there are these teachings on how my nature is totally pure and so is yours.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
 And this situation is very workable.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:24.000
 So there's a basis to grow from.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
 It's kind of just a simple thing about just the word bodhicitta.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
 You know how it's defined here on these concepts and terms.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
 But basically the mind of enlightenment.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:40.690
 So I mean just within the word is that the mind has to be, it's the mind being turned to it towards

00:12:40.690 --> 00:12:41.000
 enlightenment.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:47.000
 So we have to have at first this sense of what is enlightenment, what's so great about it.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:50.000
 So contemplating that first.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:55.000
 So we have like a destination that we understand what we're doing.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:59.000
 And then within that, with is bodhicitta also.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:06.000
 Many, many times Vibhiches define it as the combination of love, compassion and wisdom.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:12.000
 So like in this paragraph we're talking about love and compassion and wisdom.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
 Like all three really are essential.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
 So just thinking about the definition of the word is basically what I'm saying.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
 Just like have that in mind.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:28.000
 That wisdom is an essential component and the wisdom is what takes it to an enlightened perspective

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:28.000
.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:33.000
 Because with love and compassion which is so wonderful and so essential too,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:37.000
 then that's what the point of we're benefiting.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:42.000
 Without the wisdom it stays, it's not a liberative pattern.

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:46.000
 This kind of like what makes everything boundless and transcendent.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
 Big.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:56.000
 That whole boundless quality of like in his commentary on the words of my perfect teacher,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:05.000
 Vibhavacham has this beautiful section on like how bodhicitta begins to increase.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
 And he says the essence of bodhicitta is the four boundless.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
 But boundless means includes all sentient beings.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
 That's the trick.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:23.000
 So he says the four boundless love, compassion, sympathetic joy and then impartiality or equanimity

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:23.000
.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:28.000
 He says even though they have love in the first list as the first one,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:33.000
 in the pith instructions when you should start with impartiality,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.750
 you should start with basically just like what you guys were saying too and like what Drachma was

00:14:37.750 --> 00:14:38.000
 saying.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:41.000
 All beings want to be happy.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:46.000
 We're all the same, we have that common, whatever else we don't have in common,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:51.000
 we do all have in common that we want to be happy.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
 And then like what Lai was saying,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:57.000
 reflecting on the fact that you've been in all these different kinds of relationships with,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:02.600
 of course this is Buddhism, we're talking about what the Buddha taught which he taught reincarn

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:03.000
ation,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
 he taught we've been in these relationships with each other forever.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
 Like we've been enemies, we've been friends, we've been all that to each other

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:17.000
 and the common thread is we all want to be happy but we're not.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:22.000
 So recognizing that all the troubles that we are going through, just like you are,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.000
 this other person who's your enemy is also going through those troubles.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:32.000
 Even though we tend to think, oh yay, my enemy is going through that trouble, yes.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:38.000
 That's usually the usual reaction but I think something about that,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:44.000
 being able to take that perspective and being able to recognize that humanity

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:52.000
 is just like the total foundation building block of equalizing, you know,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:57.000
 has seen that view.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
 Yeah, it goes into the second topic point.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:06.000
 So I'll do a quick summary of this second section of the chapter really quickly.

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:12.000
 Venerable Kembor Rinpoche said that it's only with bodhichitta that we can realize enlightenment.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
 And without bodhichitta we cannot realize enlightenment.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:19.000
 That bodhichitta is working to free all beings from suffering

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:25.000
 and establishing them in enlightenment without any concern for your own welfare.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:32.000
 The root of bodhichitta is compassion and the root of compassion is loving kindness.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.000
 And then your love and compassion should include all beings

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:38.000
 and of course now these qualities are limited

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:42.000
 but with training over time they can become infinite.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
 And that everything becomes easier as we become more familiar with it

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:50.000
 and that bodhichitta is no exception to this, it works in the same way.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:55.000
 As we train in it more and more it becomes easier and easier to recognize and generate.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:17:02.000
 And then seeing that all beings are equal, we all want happiness and none of us want to suffer.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:09.000
 And then they talk about how the relative aspect of bodhichitta has two subdivisions or two parts.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:15.000
 On the one hand is the wishing or the aspiring relative bodhichitta wanting to help others.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:22.000
 And then there's the actualizing or engaging bodhichitta where we actually work to help others.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
 We put that aspiration into practice, we perform it.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:32.000
